Packages

For this lab, we need tidyverse and nycflights13 packages. Use install.packages() to install them if you havent yet.

Starwars

First, we need to load our Starwars data set, which is in the tidyverse package. Lets load it up.

library(tidyverse)
glimpse(starwars)

Before we jump in, Id like to clean up the hair_color variable. This variable is simply too detailed and has too many hair colors as it is so that only a few of these colors has enough observations. Lets create a frequency table to see if how many observations each hair color have.

starwars %>% 
  count(hair_color)
## # A tibble: 13 x 2
##    hair_color        n
##    <chr>         <int>
##  1 auburn            1
##  2 auburn, grey      1
##  3 auburn, white     1
##  4 black            13
##  5 blond             3
##  6 blonde            1
##  7 brown            18
##  8 brown, grey       1
##  9 grey              1
## 10 none             37
## 11 unknown           1
## 12 white             4
## 13 <NA>              5

Well, most of the colors has only one observation, so it makes less sense to code them as a separate category. What Im going to do is to keep the three hair colors (black, brown, blond), and have all the other colors coded as others. That way, we will have four categories of hair color, each of which will have a sufficient sample size. Im using the fct_other() function from the forcats package, which is also part of the tidyverse.

starwars <- starwars %>%
  mutate(hair_color2 = 
           fct_other(hair_color, 
                     keep = c("black", "brown", "blond")
                     )
         )

The data is ready. Lets graph out the data using different types.

Distribution

Histogram

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(x = height)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10)

Density plots

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(x = height)) +
  geom_density() #<<

Side-by-side box plots

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(y = height, 
                                      x = gender)) + #<<
  geom_boxplot()

Violin plots

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(y = height, x = gender)) +
  geom_violin()

Ranking

Bar plots

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(x = gender)) +
  geom_bar()

Segmented bar plots, counts

ggplot(data = starwars, mapping = aes(x = gender, 
                                      fill = hair_color)) + #<<
  geom_bar()

See the fill option in the aesthetic mapping. fill = hair_color. We want to fill the bar based on different hair colors. Make sense, right?

Segmented bar plots, counts

ggplot(data = starwars, 
       mapping = aes(x = gender, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip()

coord_flip() is used for flipping coordinates to its side.

Segmented bar plots, proportions

You can set the position argument in geom_bar() to fill to make the x-axis as proportions.

ggplot(data = starwars, 
       mapping = aes(x = gender, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y = "proportion")

Grouped bar plots

ggplot(data = starwars, 
       mapping = aes(x = gender, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge") + #<<
  coord_flip()

geom_bar() has the position argument set to dodge to make the bars grouped together.

Pie chart

To make a pie chart, we need an extra step for creating a frequency variable of hair_color2.

starwars2 <- starwars %>% 
  count(hair_color2)
starwars2
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   hair_color2     n
##   <fct>       <int>
## 1 black          13
## 2 blond           3
## 3 brown          18
## 4 Other          48
## 5 <NA>            5

The new data set, starwars2, has now two variables - hair_color2 and n.Lets make a pie chart using this data frame.

ggplot(data = starwars2, mapping = aes(x="", y = n, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0)

Look at how I changed the geom_bar() setting. The stat option is now identity, rather than its default count because weve created a count variable n.This code also has another function coord_polar(), which is used to make the chart in circle. If we take this function out,

ggplot(data = starwars2, mapping = aes(x="", y = n, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white")

its then just a rectangular shape. Now we understand how coord_polar() shapes the chart.

You can change the color scheme as well.

ggplot(data = starwars2, mapping = aes(x="", y = n, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0) +
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "GnBu", name = "Hair Color") + #<<
  labs(title = "Hair color of Starwars characters")

scale_fill_brewer() has the palette option set to GnBu. Lets change it to something else, like BuGn.

ggplot(data = starwars2, mapping = aes(x="", y = n, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0) +
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "BuGn", name = "Hair Color") + #<<
  labs(title = "Hair color of Starwars characters")

Or, Accent

ggplot(data = starwars2, mapping = aes(x="", y = n, fill = hair_color2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0) +
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent", name = "Hair Color") + #<<
  labs(title = "Hair color of Starwars characters")

You can see how it works, right? Simply specify the color scheme you want to the palette option. To see the list of available color schemes, check this link: https://colorbrewer2.org/#type=sequential&scheme=GnBu&n=5.

NYC flights in 2013

In this example, were using another data set-nyclights13. Since its not part of tidyverse, you first need to install the package using this command: install.packages("nycflights13") You only need to install it once. After that, you can simply call the package using library() as we do with any other packages.

library(nycflights13)
dow = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")
flights1 <- flights %>% 
  mutate(total_delay = dep_delay + arr_delay,
         date = as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep='-')),
         weekday = factor(weekdays(date), levels= dow))
flights1 %>% 
  select(date, origin, total_delay)
## # A tibble: 336,776 x 3
##    date       origin total_delay
##    <date>     <chr>        <dbl>
##  1 2013-01-01 EWR             13
##  2 2013-01-01 LGA             24
##  3 2013-01-01 JFK             35
##  4 2013-01-01 JFK            -19
##  5 2013-01-01 LGA            -31
##  6 2013-01-01 EWR              8
##  7 2013-01-01 EWR             14
##  8 2013-01-01 LGA            -17
##  9 2013-01-01 JFK            -11
## 10 2013-01-01 LGA              6
## #  with 336,766 more rows

I created three new variables: total_delay, date, weekday. Total_delay is the sum of the two types of delay (departure and arrival). Date is to convert three separate date information (year, month, day) into one date variable, and weekday is to find out what the day of week is for each date. There are some new functions used in this code such as as.Date() and weekdays(). We will see these functions later, so lets move on for now. Its enough that you are aware of the fact that R can do this stuff (When needed, we can google it).

Average flight delay by month

The original data seems too large to visualize it. Lets average them for each month.

avg_delay_month <- flights1 %>% 
  group_by(month, origin) %>% 
  summarise(mean_delay = mean(total_delay, na.rm=TRUE))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'month' (override with `.groups` argument)

Bar chart

ggplot(avg_delay_month, aes(x=month, y=mean_delay)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") #<<

We can now see clearly the trend of flight delays over the year. One thing to note is that the month on x-axis has decimal points like 7.5 month. Thats because R treated month as a continuous variable because its integer. Hence, 7.5 month is possible.

To resolve this issue, we need to make month as a factor variable using as.factor() (you can also use factor() instead). Factor is the data type R uses for storing categorical variables (discrete values)

Bar chart for each airport

ggplot(avg_delay_month, aes(x=as.factor(month), y=mean_delay)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  facet_grid(.~origin) #<<

Notice as.factor(month) has removed the decimal point.

Grouped bar chart

ggplot(avg_delay_month, aes(x=as.factor(month), y=mean_delay, fill=origin)) + #<<
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity") + #<<
  labs(x="Month",
       y="Average delay",
       fill="Airport",
       title="Average delay by airport")

What day of week is the worst for flight delays?

To answer this question, we need to average the data over month as well as day of week.

delay_weekday <- flights1 %>% 
  group_by(month, weekday, origin) %>% 
  summarise(mean_delay = mean(total_delay, na.rm=TRUE))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'month', 'weekday' (override with `.groups` argument)

geom_tile() is used to create a heatmap. The basic heatmap chart is as simple as adding geom_tile().

ggplot(delay_weekday, aes(as.factor(month), weekday, fill=mean_delay)) + 
  geom_tile() + #<<
  labs(x="Month",
     y="Day of week",
     title = "Flight delay heatmap", 
     fill="Delay")

To make it prettier, or more informative, you may want to adjust its color schemes as well as other design options. I used scale_fill_gradient() to change the color, but you can also use scale_fill_distiller() with the palette option as we did before.

ggplot(delay_weekday, aes(as.factor(month), weekday, fill=mean_delay)) + 
  geom_tile(colour = "white") + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="red") + #<<
  facet_grid(.~origin) + #<<
  labs(x="Month",
       y="Day of week",
       title = "Flight delay heatmap", 
       fill="Delay")
